# Public Prosecutor _v_ Teo Kai Xiang  

### \[2022\] SGDC 184

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9138/2022/01.\]

19 August 2022

### District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

## Background

1       The accused, Mr Teo Kai Xiang, a 34-year old male Singapore citizen had pleaded guilty on 13 June 2022 to the following charge:

> **DAC 909077-2021**

Charge

> are charged that you, on 1 November 2020, at or about 11.30 a.m., along Yishun Ring Road towards the direction of Yishun Avenue 5, Singapore, did drive a motorcar, SLZ 7003 S, without reasonable consideration for other persons using the road, to wit, by failing to give way to a motorcycle, FZ 8298 Y, when making a right turn into a non-signalised T-junction of Block 165 Yishun Ring Road, which resulted in a collision with the said motorcycle that was proceeding straight from your opposite direction, and consequently, caused the death of one Leong Chee Kiong, a 50-year-old male, who was the rider of the said motorcycle, and thus by such driving, you have thereby committed an offence under Section 65(1)(b) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) punishable under Section 65(2)(a) r/w Section 65(6)(a) of the same Act.

2       One remaining charge in **DAC 909078-2021** - a charge under s 65(1)(_b_) punishable under s 65(5)(_a_) of the RTA was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing. The matter was adjourned to 22 July 2022 for the Prosecution’s address on the sentence and for the Defence to prepare the plea in mitigation.

3       On 22 July 2022, after carefully considering the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence and the Defence’s plea in mitigation, I sentenced the accused to 15 weeks’ imprisonment and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of eight years with effect from the date of release.

4       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision had filed his Notice of Appeal against my sentence on 22 July 2022. He is presently on bail pending the hearing of his appeal.

5       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

## The Salient Facts

#### Involved Parties

6       The accused is a 34-year old male Singaporean and the driver of motorcar bearing registration number SLZ7003S (the “car”).

7       The deceased is Mr Leong Chee Kiong. He was a 50-year-old male Malaysian and the rider of the motorcycle bearing registration number FZ8298Y at the material time of the offence (the “motorcycle”).

8       The first involved party is Mr Han Yee Yen, the driver of the motorcar bearing registration number SDV8850Y at the time of the incident (“1st involved party’s car”).

#### First Information Report

9       On 1 November 2020, at 11.32am, police received a call with the text message stating, “Car and Motorbike accident”. The incident location was provided as Apartment Block 165 Yishun Ring Road, Singapore, 760165.

#### Facts in relation to the 1st Charge DAC-909077-2021

10     Investigations revealed that on 1 November 2020 at or about 11.30am, the accused was driving his car on lane 1 of the 2-lane road along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 5, Singapore. The accused then made a right turn into the non-signalised T-junction, leading to the entrance and exit of the open space carpark of Block 165 Yishun Ring Road (“open-space carpark”).

11     When the accused made the right turn, he failed to give way to the deceased’s motorcycle, which was travelling straight ahead in the opposite direction along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2, Singapore. The car did not come to a complete stop when checking for oncoming vehicles before negotiating the right turn into the open-space carpark.

12     The accused’s failure to give way to the deceased’s motorcycle resulted in a collision between the two vehicles. Due to the collision, the deceased’s motorcycle veered to the left and collided into the front right portion of the 1st involved party’s car, which was stationary at the exit of the open-space carpark. The accused heard a collision and alighted to check on what had happened. He then saw the deceased lying down on the road, facing up. Just before the collision, the 1st involved party had noticed an unknown object coming towards his car from his right, and thereafter felt a hard impact on the front right portion of his car.

![](data:image;base64,)

![](data:image;base64,)

13     The final resting position of the accused’s car showed that the car’s right tyre had crossed over into the exit lane of the open-space carpark.

![](data:image;base64,)

#### Injuries Sustained by the Deceased

14     The deceased was conveyed to Khoo Teck Puat Hospital (KTPH) after the accident. According to the deceased’s medical report prepared by Dr Tang Man Hon of KTPH, he was not conscious when he arrived at KTPH. He sustained the following injuries consistent with a road traffic accident:

> (a)     a traumatic brain injury with intra-cranial haemorrhage;

> (b)     a right rib fracture with haemothorax and pneumothorax and

> (c)     multiple facial fractures.

15     The deceased underwent emergency resuscitative thoracotomy and haemostasis on 1 November 2020 and was managed post-operatively in the intensive care unit. However, the deceased succumbed to his injuries and was pronounced dead by Dr Seow Yi Heng on 1 November 2020 at 11.00 p.m. The deceased’s autopsy report prepared by Dr Wu Jia Hao (“Dr Wu”) of the Health Sciences Authority’s (HSA) Forensic Medicine Division concluded the cause of the deceased’s death to be due to head injury, and that the injuries observed on the deceased was consistent with a motor vehicle collision.

#### Vehicle Damage

16     The following damage was found on the deceased’s motorcycle:

> (a)     Headlight cover damaged;

> (b)     Headlight damaged;

> (c)     Front forks damaged;

> (d)     Front mudguard damaged;

> (e)     Radiator damaged;

> (f)     Right handlebar damaged;

> (g)     Right side mirror damaged;

> (h)     Front brake lever damaged;

> (i)     Petrol tank damaged;

> (j)     Right rear side cover damaged;

> (k)     Right front footrest damaged;

> (l)     Rear brake pedal damaged;

> (m)     Left front footrest damaged;

> (n)     Exhaust muffler damaged and

> (o)     Top box rack damaged.

17     The front bumper of the first involved party’s car was damaged. The front bonnet and front bumper of the accused’s car were damaged.

18     At the material time of the incident, weather was clear, traffic was light and road surface was dry.

#### Mechanical inspection of vehicles

19     The steering system of the motorcycle was damaged because of the accident but the braking system was found to be in serviceable condition. The two tyres of the motorcycle were found to be in serviceable condition and sufficiently inflated for vehicular operation. A mechanical inspection conducted on the motorcycle could not determine whether there was any possible mechanical failure to the motorcycle that may have contributed to the accident.

20     Based on a mechanical inspection of the accused’s car on 8 January 2021, the car’s engine system, transmission system, steering system and braking system were all in serviceable condition. There was no evidence to suggest that there was possible mechanical failure and/or abnormal behaviour to the motorcar that may have caused and/or contributed to the accident.

#### Collision Configuration, Speed and Visibility Analysis Report by HSA

21     Senior Forensic Scientist, Lee Rui Lin of HSA’s Forensic Chemistry and Physics Laboratory prepared a collision configuration, speed and visibility analysis report on the accident (“HSA’s report”). The HSA report stated that the deceased’s motorcycle was more likely to be travelling in the direction of Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2 prior to the collision. The accused’s car was likely to be turning in from Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 5 into the open-space car park. The front of the accused’s car collided with the right side of the deceased’s motorcycle with the motorcycle more likely to be upright at the collision and the deceased’s motorcycle was most likely to already have fallen when it collided with the 1st involved party’s car.

22     With regards to the speed, the HSA report at \[20\] calculated the projection speed of the motorcycle to be 32km/h to 44 km/h. Further \[21\] of the HSA Report, states that, “the calculated projection speed of the rider of 32km/h to 44km/h serves as an indication of the speed of the motorcycle…It is not known if the collision between the Toyota and the motorcycle could have affected the projection speed of the rider.”

23     With regards to visibility, the HSA report at \[27\] states that it is unlikely that the accused’s view of the deceased’s motorcycle would be completely obstructed and the unobstructed distance of the curved road along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2 for the accused would be about 65 to 89m upstream from the right turn which the accused made.

24     The HSA’s supplemental report at page 7 at \[10b.iii\] states, “it is agreed that the travel speed of the motorcycle would have affected the amount of time it was available to be seen. As the exact speed of the motorcycle prior to the collision is not known, the time available to be seen for the estimated distance of 65m to 89m was estimated based on a range of hypothetical speed, as illustrated in Table B2”.

![](data:image;base64,)

25     Based on Table B2 and the projection speed of the motorcycle which provides an indication of the speed that the motorcycle was travelling, the approximate time available for the accused to see the motorcycle would be somewhere between 6 to 8 seconds, and at the very least, 4 seconds.

#### Conclusion

26     By virtue of the foregoing, the accused had driven his motorcar without reasonable consideration for other persons using the road, to wit, by failing to give way to a motorcycle, FZ8298Y, when making a right turn into a non-signalised T-junction of Block 165 Yishun Ring Road, which resulted in a collision with the said motorcycle that was proceeding straight from his opposite direction. This collision consequently caused the death of the deceased who was the rider of the said motorcycle, and thus by such driving, he has thereby committed an offence under s 65(1)(_b_) punishable under s 65(2)(_a_) read with s 65(6)(_a_) of the RTA.

## Sentencing

### Prescribed Penalty

27     The prescribed penalty for an offence under s 65(1)(_a_) and punishable under 65(2)(_a_) read with 65(6)(_a_) of the Road Traffic Act (“RTA”) is fine not exceeding $10,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding three years or to both.

28     In addition, pursuant to s 65(6)(_a_) of the RTA, the offender is liable to a mandatory disqualification order for all classes of vehicles for at least eight years.

## Antecedents

29     The accused is untraced.

## Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

30     The Prosecution had submitted for a sentence of at least five months’ imprisonment with the mandatory 8 years’ disqualification for all classes from the date of release.

31     In support of its sentencing position, the Prosecution had relied on _Public Prosecutor v Selvakumar Ranjan_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGDC 252</span> at \[26\] (“_Selvakumar_”) where a district court had set out a sentencing framework for offences under s 65(2)(_a_) Road Traffic for an accused person who claims trial This is in light of the need for deterrence for road traffic offences so that our public roads would be safer. It was submitted that adjustments are to be made for plead-guilty cases by taking into account the offender-specific factors (at \[136\]).

32     It was submitted that in terms of harm, the district court had stated that in fatal traffic accidents, the only eventuality of harm caused is death. There is therefore, no distinction in the level of harm in relation to death caused to the victim (at \[119\]). Nevertheless, it was submitted that in the present case, that there was harm caused in relation to property damage. The deceased’s motorcycle was heavily damaged.

33     In _Selvakumar_, the district court had set out a functional definition in relation to the level of culpability as follows:

34     It was the Prosecution’s case that the accused’s culpability is in the middle of the low band in view of the following:

> (a)     There were no signs of dangerous driving. The accused failed to give way to the deceased who had the right of way. However, the accused’s culpability is increased based on HSA’s configuration, speed and visibility report, the deceased’s motorcycle would have been visible to the accused 65m to 89m upstream from the point of the accused’s right turn. The deceased’s motorcycle would be visible to the accused for at least 6 to 8 seconds. It was submitted that, the fact that the accused could reasonably have seen the victim, yet still failed to give way to him causing his death, increases the accused’s culpability.

> (b)     The accused admitted that he had not come to a complete stop before making a right turn when he was checking for oncoming traffic. While it was not strictly necessary for the accused to have come to a complete stop before making the right turn, it was submitted that the failure to make a complete stop would have impacted the accused’s ability to spot oncoming traffic and give way to the deceased’s motorcycle which had the right of way. It was submitted that this increases the accused’s culpability.

> (c)     The accused faces one other charge for inconsiderate driving under s 65(1)(_b_) and punishable under s 65(5)(_a_) of the RTA that was taken into consideration. The accused’s inconsiderate driving had led to the deceased’s motorcycle also colliding into the 1st involved party’s car which caused damage to the car.

It was submitted that the appropriate sentencing range would thus be at least six to 12 months’ imprisonment, before considering the offender-specific factors.

#### Offender-specific factors

35     The Prosecution had considered the fact that the accused had pleaded guilty. It was also noted that the accused did not have any antecedents and had a clean driving record.

36     It was the Prosecution’s case that considering both the harm and culpability and the relevant offender-specific factors, that an imprisonment term of at least five months’ imprisonment with 8 years mandatory disqualification would be appropriate.

## Mitigation

37     In his written plea in mitigation, Defence Counsel Mr. Sunil Sudheesan had set out his client’s personal background as well as the circumstances that led to the commission of the offence. The Defence sought the imposition of a high fine and in the alternative, a short custodial sentence of around four to six weeks’ imprisonment. It was submitted that it was agreed that the mandatory 8 years disqualification order be imposed. It was the Defence’s case that the accused’s driving behaviour in the present case was careless but he had not displayed an “egregious irresponsible” driving behaviour that would have otherwise warranted an increased sentence.

#### Circumstances of the present case

38     In the present case, the accused had intended to make a right turn into the entrance leading to the open space carpark of Block 165 Yishun Ring Road. According to the Defence, the accused had ascertained that it was safe before he turned right into the carpark. As the accused had just driven over a significantly sized hump (Figure 2) immediately before making the right turn into the carpark, this necessarily meant that he had slowed down and was approaching the carpark at a low speed. It was submitted that he had done checks for oncoming traffic from the opposite side of the road and the entrance of the carpark. According to the Defence, he had also signalled his intention to make the right turn by switching on his right indicator before he reached the T-junction.

39     It was emphasised that there was no Stop line where the accused made the right turn. It was the Defence’s position that there was no legal requirement for the accused to have come to a complete stop before making the right turn. The fact that he did not stop and thereby failed to give way to the motorcyclist, is inherent in the offence he had been charged with and convicted of.

#### Motorcyclist’s speed

40     In the HSA report, it was estimated that the “projection speed” of motorcyclist to be about 32 km/h to 44 km/h at the point of impact. It was the Defence’s case that this estimated projection speed of the motorcyclist served only as an indication of the speed of the motorcycle just prior to the collision. There were factors, including any brakes applied by the motorcyclist if the motorcyclist had been travelling at a high speed that could have affected the estimated projection speed. It was the Defence’s case that it was not known whether motorcyclist had applied some deceleration while negotiating the bend and it was agreed that the calculated projection speed did not account for this deceleration, if any. Hence, the specific speed the motorcyclist was travelling at the material time was unknown.

41     It was further highlighted that in the HSA supplementary report that the amount of time the accused had to see the motorcycle was primarily dependent on the actual speed at which the motorcyclist was travelling at. It was suggested that the accused’s ability to have seen the motorcyclist in good time was affected by the motorcyclist’s speed at the time he was negotiating the bend. This speed remained unknown.

42     It was the Defence’s case that the accused had immediately stopped his car when he felt the impact. He had alighted from his vehicle to check on what had happened and rendered assistance to the motorcyclist, as best as he could, given the circumstances. He had called the ambulance and cooperated fully with investigations thereafter.

43     It was also the Defence’s case that it was not clear whether the helmet that was worn by the motorcyclist was compliant with the safety standard regulated by the authorities. An approved helmet would have been tested to ensure that the helmet has sufficient protective padding material and structural integrity to absorb or dissipate impact forces from reaching the motorcyclist’s head. An approved helmet should also have been tested for the effectiveness of the retention system that would keep the helmet on the head of the motorcyclist.

44     It was highlighted that sometime in or around end 2021, a new sizeable hump with speed regulating strips were built on the same stretch of road at which the incident occurred, around the bend. It was suggested that the new built-in feature on the road is indicative that the authorities recognise the dangers of vehicles, especially motorcyclists, approaching the bend at high speeds and have therefore put in place interventionist features to mandate that vehicles slow down as they approach the bend.

#### Submissions on sentence

45     It was submitted that the Defence agreed with the Prosecution that the sentencing framework as set out in _Selvakumar_ is relevant in the present case. However, the sentencing framework applies to cases where accused persons are convicted after trial. Accordingly, in the present case, the appropriate downward adjustments must be made given that the accused had pleaded guilty. It was the Defence’s case that based on _Selvakumar_, the accused did not exhibit any dangerous driving behaviour and was regrettably careless in executing the right turn into the carpark as he failed to do a comprehensive enough check. It was one lapse, and he regretted it fully.

46     It was the Defence’s position that while the amendments to the RTA increased the Court’s sentencing powers in relation to negligent driving causing death, it must not be interpreted to mean that there ought to be a blanket increase in the sentences imposed. Prior to the 2019 amendments to the RTA, cases of inconsiderate driving resulting in death would have typically been prosecuted under s 304A(b) of the Penal Code (Chapter 224, 2008 Rev Ed)(the “Penal Code”). The Defence referred to two precedent cases under s 304A(b) of the Penal Code namely _PP v Wai Ling Yee_ (MAC-901399-2021 on 23 July 2021) and _PP v Lee Shang Bin Melvyn_ <span class="citation">\[2012\] SGDC 354</span> and urged due consideration to be given as these cases remain good law. It was submitted that the maximum fine of $10,000 would be appropriate in the present case.

47     The Defence also referred to _PP v Muhammad Adham Bin Ishak_ (DAC-925942-2021 on 1 June 2022)(“_Adham_”) where the offender had pleaded guilty to one charge under s 65(1)(_a_) and punishable under s 65(2)(_a_) read with 65(6)(_a_) of the RTA. It was submitted that _Adham_ provides useful guidance as to the appropriate length of imprisonment term to be imposed as the level of culpability was similar to the present case – it was ultimately a momentary lapse of judgement in failing to keep a proper look out.

48     It was further submitted that one distinguishing factor in _Adham_ was that the offender was driving a motor van _ie_ a larger vehicle. It is trite that the courts typically regard this as more aggravating as it would be incumbent on such drivers to exercise greater care. Nonetheless, it was accepted that the accused faced one other charge that had been taken into consideration, given that there was a consequential collision to a motorcar in the vicinity. It was for this reason that the court was urged to consider a sentence of around four to six weeks’ imprisonment, if it was of the view that the custodial threshold had been crossed.

## Prosecution’s Reply

49     In response to the Defence’s submissions that the accused had made checks for oncoming traffic and made the turn safely, it was the Prosecution’s position that there was no evidence that the accused did signal his intention to turn before making that turn. It was highlighted that the HSA report had concluded that the deceased’s motorcycle would have reasonably been seen by the accused 65m to 89m upstream from the turn. The only logical conclusion was that the accused could have seen the motorcycle and yet failed to give way to him.

50     It was submitted that the Defence had raised various precedents but they were of no relevance to the present case as these were offences under s 304A(b) of the Penal Code and these cases were also decided before the amendments to the RTA took effect on 1st November 2019. The RTA amendments, which have been stated clearly in the parliamentary debates as well as court cases, have highlighted that the enhanced punishments impose stronger deterrence and keep public roads safer. Consequently, the increase in sentencing range reflects that policy consideration and the jump in sentencing ranges are not inappropriate.

51     In relation to the unreported precedent of _Adham_, it was further submitted that while this was a case after the RTA amendments took effect, it was still of limited precedential value given that it was not a reported decision. It was highlighted that one major consideration of that case was that the offender was 22 years old and this was clearly a consideration that the Prosecutor had submitted on in his address on sentence.

52     It was the Prosecution’s position that the Defence’s submissions that the collision was due to the motorcyclist’s speed or the fact that he had worn an unsafe helmet that was not approved by the authorities were entirely speculative. In fact, based on the HSA report, the projection speed of the motorcyclist was estimated to be 32 to 44 kilometres per hour. Even if the Prosecution acknowledge that these were indications and estimations provided by the HSA based on indicated speeds of the motorcyclist, in the absence of any other expert opinions, it was submitted that this was the best estimation to rely on.

## Decision on sentence

### S 65(1) of the RTA

53     S 65(1) of the RTA encapsulates the primary offence of driving without due care and attention or reasonable consideration for other persons using the road. The subsequent subsections from ss 65(2) to 65(4) are the penalty prescribing provisions, each tiered according to the degree of hurt caused and for s 65(5), for any other case of non-personal injury or potential harm. The present offence under s 65(1) of the RTA was enacted on 1 November 2019, following the passing of the Road Traffic (Amendment) Act 2019 (Act 19 of 2019).

54     Presently under s 65(1) of the RTA, a first offender falling within the lowest end of the spectrum of non-personal injury or potential harm is liable under s 65(5)(_a_) to a fine not exceeding $1,500 or to imprisonment not exceeding six months or to both. At the highest end of the spectrum, where the most serious harm _ie_ death is caused, a first offender is liable under s 65(2)(_a_) to a fine not exceeding $10,000 or to imprisonment not exceeding three years or to both. In addition, enhanced penalties as well as minimum disqualification periods were introduced for offences where death or grievous hurt is caused as well as for a repeat offender, a serious offender as well as a serious repeat offender.

55     The present case falls under the category of most serious harm as death had resulted as a direct consequence of the accused’s irresponsible driving. As at the date of my decision there is no existing sentencing framework enunciated by the High Court for offences under s 65(1) which are punishable under s 65(2)(_a_) of the RTA.

56     In _Wu Zhi Yong v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 261</span> (“_Wu Zhi Yong_”) at \[27\], in his consideration of the appropriate sentencing framework for an offence under s 64(2C)(_a_) read with s 64(2C)(_c_) of the RTA, Sundaresh Menon CJ had observed at \[27\] that in some of these situations where death is caused, the nature of the harm ceases to be a relevant differentiating factor for the purposes of sentencing offenders falling within the applicable provision.

57     In the present case, both the Prosecution and the Defence had relied on _Selvakumar_, where the district judge had proposed a sentencing framework for offences punishable under s 65(2)(_a_) of the RTA for offenders who claimed trial. In that case, the district court had adopted the two-stage, five-step approach in _Logachev Vladislav v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 4 SLR 609</span> (“_Logachev-_hybrid approach”) in drawing up this sentencing framework. As the only eventuality of the harm caused in fatal accidents is death, the court was of the view at \[119\] that there was no distinction in the level of harm. Hence in that case for the purpose of the sentencing framework under s 65(2)(_a_) of the RTA, the focus was dealing with the degree of culpability of an accused. The sentencing framework drawn up by the district court in _Selvakumar_ is set out below.

58     I was mindful that as there was no appeal against this decision, there is no appellate determination on the appropriateness of the suggested sentencing framework. Nevertheless, I agreed with this sentencing approach as well as the range of custodial sentences within each of the sentencing bands in _Selvakumar_ as it utilises the entire sentencing range stipulated in s 65(2)(_a_) of the RTA. For such offences which falls under the category of most serious harm, as a form of punishment, the protection of the public as well as deterrence, the imposition of custodial sentences should be the norm unless there are exceptional circumstances to warrant the imposition of a fine.

#### Sentencing approach

## My decision on sentence

59     In the present case, the Prosecution had sought a custodial sentence of five months’ imprisonment. In contrast, the Defence had sought the imposition of the maximum fine of $10,000 and in the alternative, a sentence of four to six weeks’ imprisonment. It was agreed that the minimum disqualification period of eight years for all classes of vehicles should be imposed in the present case.

## Application of the framework

#### Step 1

60     For step 1, in terms of the accused’s culpability, I found that the accused’s culpability fell within the low band in _Selvakumar_. The offence was committed when the accused made a right turn into the non-signalised T-junction, leading to the entrance and exit of the open space carpark of Block 165 Yishun Ring Road. Although there were no signs of dangerous driving, the accused failed to give way to the deceased who had the right of way. Based on HSA’s configuration, speed and visibility report, the deceased’s motorcycle would have been visible to the accused 65m to 89m upstream from the point of the accused’s right turn.

61     In addition, the deceased’s motorcycle would have been visible to the accused for at least 6 to 8 seconds. Hence, I agreed with the Prosecution that the accused could reasonably have seen the deceased, yet still failed to give way to him. As a result of this failure, the front of the accused’s car had collided with the right side of the deceased’s motorcycle while he was riding along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2. I further agreed with the Prosecution that the fact that accused could reasonably have seen the deceased and yet failed to give way to him increased the accused’s level of culpability.

62     Further, the accused admitted that he had not come to a complete stop before making a right turn when he was checking for oncoming traffic. While it was not strictly necessary for the accused to have come to a complete stop before making the right turn, I agreed with the Prosecution that the failure to make a complete stop would have impacted the accused’s ability to spot oncoming traffic and give way to the deceased’s motorcycle which had the right of way. Hence, I did not regard the Defence’s submissions the accused must have slowed down as he had just driven over a significantly sized hump immediately before making the right turn as a mitigating factor.

63     It was evident that the accused had failed to make the necessary checks for vehicles travelling along both sides of Yishun Ring Road and ensured that he could proceed safely before making the right turn into the non-signalised T-junction leading to the entrance and exit of the open space carpark of Block 165 Yishun Ring Road. As the deceased was travelling along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2, it was clear that he had the right of way as opposed to the accused who was turning right from the opposite side of Yishun Ring Road.

64     I disagreed with the Defence’s submissions that the accused had done checks for oncoming traffic from the opposite side of the road and the entrance of the carpark as the above facts did not support this position. I also agreed with the Prosecution’s position that the Defence’s submissions that the collision was due to the deceased’s speed or the fact that he had worn an unsafe helmet that was not approved by the authorities were entirely speculative as it was unsupported by objective evidence.

65     In terms of the harm caused, apart from the most serious form of harm being caused to the deceased, I had considered that there was also property damage in the present case. The deceased’s motorcycle was heavily damaged when the accused’s car collided into his motorcycle.

66     In the present case, the accused faced one other charge for inconsiderate driving under s 65(1)(_b_) and punishable under s 65(5)(_a_) of the RTA that was taken into consideration. The accused’s inconsiderate driving had led to the deceased’s motorcycle also colliding into the 1st involved party’s car which caused damage to the car. This is another factor that increased the accused’s level of culpability.

#### Step 2

67     At the second step, the court is to identify the applicable sentencing range and based on the framework, I agreed with the Prosecution that the applicable range was six to twelve months’ imprisonment.

#### Step 3

68     The third step requires the identification of the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. Having considered the evidence as set out above, I was of the view the appropriate starting point would be six months’ imprisonment.

#### Step 4

69     At the fourth step, adjustments should be made to the starting point to take into account the offender-specific factors as the _Selvakumar_ sentencing framework applies to an accused who claims trial.

#### Offender-specific factors

70     In the present case, I had considered the accused’s plea of guilt and that he was a first offender. I did not place any weight to the Defence’s submissions that a custodial sentence is unduly harsh and would have an undue impact on the accused and his elderly parents as their health have deteriorated over the years and he is the sole breadwinner of the family. In _Public Prosecutor v Mohammed Liton Mohammed Syeed Malik_ <span class="citation">\[2008\] 1 SLR(R) 601</span> at \[98\], the Court of Appeal stated that “in the absence of very exceptional circumstances, little, if any weight should be attached to the fact that the accused’s family will suffer if the accused is imprisoned for a substantial period of time.”

71     In my view, there were no exceptional circumstances in his plea in mitigation which warranted a departure from the imposition of a custodial sentence and for a fine of $10,000 sought by the Defence. As the present proceeded charge falls under the category of most serious harm, as a form of punishment, the protection of the public as well as deterrence, the imposition of custodial sentences should be the norm unless there are exceptional circumstances to warrant the imposition of a fine.

72     I agreed with the Prosecution that the various precedents under s 304A(b) of the Penal Code referred to by the Defence were of no relevance to the present case as the present charge is under s 65(2)(_a_) of the RTA and these cases were also decided before the amendments to the RTA took effect on 1st November 2019. It is clear from the parliamentary debates that the enhanced punishments pursuant to the RTA amendments were to impose stronger deterrence and keep public roads safer. Consequently, the increase in sentencing range reflects that policy consideration and the jump in sentencing ranges is not inappropriate.

73     I also agreed with the Prosecution that the unreported precedent of _Adham_ was of limited precedential value given that it was not a reported decision. As highlighted by the Prosecution, one major consideration in that case was that the offender was 22 years old at the time of the accident. As I had dealt with that case, I am aware that when he pleaded guilty in June 2022, he was in his final year of his polytechnic studies. In his address on sentence, on account of his plea of guilt, relatively young age, and cooperation with the authorities, the Prosecution had submitted for a sentence of between one to three months’ imprisonment. In that case, a sentence of six weeks’ imprisonment and disqualification for a period eight years from release were imposed. In the present case, the accused is a 34- year-old working adult unlike the offender in _Adham_, who was of relatively young age. Hence, I disagreed with the Defence’s submissions that _Adham_ provides useful guidance as to the appropriate length of imprisonment term to be imposed as the level of culpability is similar to the present case.

74     In view of the mitigating factors in favour of the accused, the Prosecution submitted for a downward adjustment to a sentence of five months’ imprisonment. Although the Defence had similarly submitted for a downward adjustment, it had urged the imposition of around four to six weeks’ imprisonment, if the Court was of the view that the custodial threshold had been crossed.

75     All things considered, having regard to all the totality of the evidence, as the accused had pleaded guilty, I adjusted the sentence downwards to 15 weeks’ imprisonment with the minimum specified disqualification of eight years from the date of release. In the present case, the collision had occurred when the accused failed to give way to the deceased as he made a right turn at a non-signalised T-junction, the exact speed of the deceased’s motorcycle was unknown and the approximate time available for the accused to see the deceased’s motorcycle was only an estimation. I was of the view that the benefit of the doubt should be given to the accused and as such calibrated the sentence downwards accordingly to below the five months’ imprisonment sought by the Prosecution. Nevertheless, I was of the view that the sentence of four to six weeks’ imprisonment sought by the Defence was too low and would not have adequately addressed the seriousness of the offence and the severity of the harm caused.

#### Step 5

76     Lastly, in the present case it was unnecessary for me to consider the totality principle the Prosecution had proceeded on one charge.

77     In my view, the sentence of 15 weeks’ imprisonment and disqualification for a period of eight years from release in respect of DAC- 909077-2021 is just and appropriate having regard to the particular facts and circumstance of the present case.
